<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="13" type="collection and habitat data">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="13">Collection and habitat data.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="13">
This species occurs under bark of deciduous trees (
<bibRefCitation author="Bousquet, Y" journalOrPublisher="NRC Research Press, Ottawa" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" title="Coleoptera Histeridae: The Insects and Arachnids of Canada, part 24." year="2006">Bousquet and Laplante 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The only specimen from New Brunswick was collected in a Lindgren funnel trap deployed in an old red pine (
<taxonomicName class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus resinosa" order="Pinales" pageId="2" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="resinosa">Pinus resinosa</taxonomicName>
Ait.) forest. The adult was captured during June.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
